&lt;p&gt;
	&lt;b class="col_4"&gt;Biodegradation Study of Vanlube&lt;sup&gt;&lt;font size="2"&gt;&amp;reg;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/sup&gt; 972&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
	&lt;br /&gt;
	One standard test method for determining aerobic biodegradation of lubricants and their components is the Gledhill Shake flask ASTM method D-6139-97. This test method was used for evaluating the biodegradation of Vanlube&lt;sup&gt;&lt;font size="2"&gt;&amp;reg;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/sup&gt; 972. Doses of Vanlube&lt;sup&gt;&lt;font size="2"&gt;&amp;reg;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/sup&gt; 972 were subjected to the conditions of the test, and there appeared to be a dose-related response. The percent degradation was measured by the amount of carbon dioxide produced versus the theoretical amount. The amount of CO&lt;sub&gt;&lt;font size="2"&gt;2&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/sub&gt; that formed was determined by reaction of carbon dioxide with barium hydroxide, which forms barium carbonate as the product:&lt;br /&gt;
	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	It&amp;nbsp;appears that the higher levels of glycol diminish the bacterial activity. This would be expected from the biodegradation of the glycol itself where it is stated &amp;quot;biodegradable in low levels&amp;quot;. The biodegradation of Vanlube&lt;sup&gt;&lt;font size="2"&gt;&amp;reg;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/sup&gt; 972 was compared with the percent biodegradation of sodium benzoate and canola oil, which are known to have very high biodegradation and are typically used as standards. We were very delighted that Vanlube&lt;sup&gt;&lt;font size="2"&gt;&amp;reg;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/sup&gt; 972 (at low levels) is &amp;quot;readily&amp;quot; biodegradable.&lt;br /&gt;
	&lt;br /&gt;
	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;table border="0" style="font-family: arial; font-size: 10pt"&gt;
	&lt;tbody&gt;
